<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="673" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d673">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 611.419/92</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-14">
                                <hi rend="italic">December 14, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 6:45 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>1259. <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> informs me
                            that the British Government will not issue further licenses for the
                            supply of manganese to the Carnegie Steel Company, the Teneriffe Steel
                            Company, and the United States Steel Products Company, as it seems
                            evident that any shortage of this substance from which these companies
                            may be suffering is due to their having sold their previous stocks to
                            the German Government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>